    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Cemeteries that are designed as a park, in which upright memorials are not used, as originally intended by Hubert Eaton (1881-1966), the coiner of the term. They are generally characterized by open expanses of turf with either flush or other regulated gravemarkers. In the last half of the 19th century, those with flush markers were called "lawn" cemeteries.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
